<p>In comedy, it is also called aÂ comic triple.Â Two is the smallest number of points needed to establish a pattern, and comedians exploit the way peopleâ€™s minds perceive expected patterns to throw the audience off track (and make them laugh) with the 3rd element.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œLies, damned lies, and statisticsâ€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>pair makes us look for a pattern or connection â€“ the third element can therefore be an effective surprise if it then breaks the expected pattern (jokes use this).</p>

<p>Can alliterate as well:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>wine, women, and song.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Can rhyme:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>ready, steady, go.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>3rd element can have the most syllables or words, but is not necessarily the most important</p>

