<blockquote>
  <p>â€œâ€˜Come in,â€™ I say. The knob turns, and in walksÂ BadeÂ Bhai. Even withÂ beesÂ buzzing inside my head I sit up straight. This is not just another richÂ asshole. Heâ€™s theÂ assholeÂ of allÂ assholes. He flicks the cigar into the corner. Lets the door slide shut. After the click, he waits for a moment. Holds his gaze. Blinks. Then smiles. Itâ€™s the smile Iâ€™ve seen on the faces of thieves, child molesters, murderers, politicians. A smile ofÂ love. Compassion. Brotherhood.â€ (Alliteration? Anadiplosis? Tricolon? )</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œthe rich get rich, and the poor get childrenâ€ â€“ This neatly combines several rhetorical devices, with a delightful twist. The first phrase is a straight diacope. The rich are then contrasted with the poor (antithesis). The second phrase mirrors the grammar of the first, making an isocolon, but instead of getting the diacope we expect (â€˜the poor get poorâ€™), our expectations are cleverly confounded with a joke.]</p>
</blockquote>

